a, Think Great: Be Great!\n|\nI guess us folks in California are kind of straitlaced and old-fashioned.'Hahaha, I thought on the way downstairs. I never thought I'd say those words with a straight face...\n\n- J.R. Rain, Moon Bayou\n|\nGo ahead and eat your bread, a time will come when it shall get to you breath. Go ahead and leave your pen, exams will come when you shall remember the pen!\n\n- Ernest\n|\nWe gardeners are healthy, joyous, natural creatures. We are practical, patient, optimistic. We declare our optimism every year, every season, with every act of planting.\n\n- Carol Deppe, The Resilient Gardener: Food Production and Self-Reliance in Uncertain Times\n|\nWe don't focus as much in schools on educational knowledge which requires thinking and application, as we do on acquiring facts.\n\n- William\n|\n...home is a magnet that lures back even its most abstracted children. But whether tomorrow or years from now, I cannot guess.\n\n- Kate Morton, The House at Riverton\n|\nWell, that's history for you, folks. Unfair, untrue and for the most part written by folk who weren't even there.\n\n- Joanne Harris, The Gospel of Loki\n|\nTo love with expectations is, in the end, an oppressive, driven thing, and people know it when they receive it.\n\n- Mark Galli, Chaos and Grace: Discovering the Liberating Work of the Holy Spirit\n|\nWe are all born with a muscle for courage, but our education has wasted it away.\n\n- Will Jelbert, The Happiness Animal\n|\nthere were lovely things in the world, lovely that didn't endure, and the lovelier for that... Nothing endures.\n\n- Lewis Grassic Gibbon, Sunset Song\n|\nA little here and a little there will always accumulate, so why be surprised when steady, small steps take you to great places?\n\n- Richelle E. Goodrich, Making Wishes\n|\nHe sat staring before him, seeing nothing but a long line of Mortimers, inexhaustable and prolific to the end of time.\n\n- Edith Pargeter, A Bloody Field by Shrewsbury\n|\nTo hold the courage to let another witness our tears, while refuting fears invitation to shield face, is to grant the most privileged of all loving intimacies to them.\n\n- Ged\n|\nI know I've got no reason to be crying;I know that there is nowhere left to run.I know that there's no reason to be hiding,I'm just mad at everyone; mad at everyone.\n\n- Margo T. Rose, The Words\n|\nPain is a treasure, for it contains mercies.\n\n- Jalaluddin Rumi, مثنوی معنوی\n|\nYou’re destined for greatness,” Life said. “But first, I’m going to make you cry.\n\n- Matshona\n|\nIt is easy to love but difficult to forget, so love every moment to create an enormous unforgettable memory.\n\n- Debasish\n|\nThe boy Prewitt loved the songs because they gave him something, a first hint that pain might not be pointless if you could only turn it into something.\n\n- James  Jones, From Here to Eternity\n|\nFor there is never anything but the present, and if one cannot live there, one cannot live anywhere.\n\n- Alan W. Watts, The Way of Zen\n|\nLet the one in least fear, lead.\n\n- Unknown\n|\nJust as there are phantom limbs there are phantom histories, histories that are severed and discarded, but linger on as thwarted possibilities an compelling nostalgias.\n\n- Adam\n|\nMusic is forever; music should grow and mature with you, following you right on up until you die.\n\n- Paul\n|\nEvery family is dysfunctional, whether you want to admit it or not.\n\n- Shailene\n|\nIf you want to learn to do something right, watch someone who has done it successfully.\n\n- Abhishek  Kumar, The Richest Engineer\n|\nYou would be very surprise with how much positive changes that you could make in your life, if could make it your top priority to mind your own business.\n\n- Unknown\n|\nSometimes, you have to step into oblivion, in order to paint success.\n\n- Lionel\n|\nLike a turnip such a head could be blown away very easily. For where a man was weak, a woman has unmanned him. It would be a mercy to blow such a man away.\n\n- Joyce Ca